The [1 carat emerald cut diamond ring](/1-carat-emerald-cut-diamond-ring) is the most common entry point for this shape — and it comes with a decision that changes the entire value equation. A GIA-certified natural 1ct emerald cut starts at [$3,140](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29333987?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) for the stone alone. Add a [$690 solitaire setting](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/rings/petite-emerald-cut-solitaire-diamond-ring-in-14k-yellow-gold-by-james-allen-item-311196?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) and the complete ring starts at $3,830.

That same $3,830 budget buys a lab-grown 1.94ct F-VVS1 emerald cut at [$2,229](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29147824?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) plus the same $690 setting — a complete ring at $2,919. You get a 94% larger stone and spend $911 less.

This page covers the full natural 1ct emerald cut ring price table, every setting option with complete ring totals, the lab-grown alternative that disrupts the 1ct price point, size and clarity rules for this shape, and the exact buyer scenarios that determine whether natural or lab is the right call. Stone plus setting equals ring — both costs are in every table.

---

**TL;DR**

- Natural 1ct emerald cut: [GIA 1.00ct D-VS1 at **$3,140**](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29333987?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) (stone only)
- Settings: from [$690 petite solitaire](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/rings/petite-emerald-cut-solitaire-diamond-ring-in-14k-yellow-gold-by-james-allen-item-311196?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) to [$4,625 platinum bezel](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/bezel-set-emerald-cut-side-stone-diamond-engagement-ring-in-platinum-by-james-allen-item-304637?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)
- Complete natural 1ct ring: from **$3,830** (stone + setting)
- Lab alternative: [IGI 1.94ct F-VVS1 at $2,229](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29147824?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) + $690 setting = **$2,919 complete** — 2ct-class stone for $900 less than a natural 1ct ring
- Size: approximately 6.5mm × 5.0mm at 1ct — step-cut effect visible but developing
- Clarity rule: VS2 minimum in natural; SI1 will show in the step-cut facets
- At natural 1ct pricing, lab lets you step up to a 2ct stone for the same or less total spend

→ Best value 1ct ring: [GIA 1.00ct D-VS1 at $3,140](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29333987?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) + [$690 solitaire](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/rings/petite-emerald-cut-solitaire-diamond-ring-in-14k-yellow-gold-by-james-allen-item-311196?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) = **$3,830 complete**, if natural origin is the priority.

Priority: if the 1ct natural ring budget is $3,800–$4,500, the lab path gives a 2ct ring for the same money. That comparison deserves a serious look before committing to natural at this size.

