The D-VS1 at [$3,140](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29333987?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the correct starting point. VS1 is safely eye-clean in an emerald cut step facet. D color means no warmth in the stone under any lighting.

This is the minimum grade combination that lets the step-cut facets show cleanly from every angle.

The D-IF at [$5,836](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28453240?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) costs nearly double for a grade improvement (VS1 → IF) that is not visible to the naked eye at 1ct. IF clarity earns a premium that is invisible in the stone but very visible in the price tag. The D-VS1 is the stronger purchase.

The D-VVS2 at [$3,971](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29652437?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) lands between those two — the 1.06ct face-up footprint is slightly larger than an exact 1ct, which is a genuine advantage in an emerald cut.

