The [$690 petite solitaire](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/rings/petite-emerald-cut-solitaire-diamond-ring-in-14k-yellow-gold-by-james-allen-item-311196?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is purpose-built for an emerald cut — the ring was specifically designed for this shape, with prong placement matched to the stone's corners. That's a meaningful difference from a generic solitaire repurposed for the shape.

For buyers who want corner protection, the [$990 bezel](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/comfort-fit-bezel-set-solitaire-engagement-ring-in-14k-white-gold-by-james-allen-item-315709?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the best upgrade. At 1ct, the bezel's metal rim looks proportionate to the stone — at larger sizes (3ct+), the bezel can look too thick, but at 1ct the proportions work naturally.

> "At 1ct, I always tell buyers to keep the setting simple. The stone at 6.5mm × 5mm is doing its job, but it's not so large that a heavy setting makes sense. A narrow solitaire or a petite pavé band — that's the right proportion. The stone should own the look, not the setting." — Farzana, diamond advisor

---

## The 6.5mm Table

At 1ct, an emerald cut diamond measures approximately 6.5mm long by 5.0mm wide. At this size, the step-cut's defining visual property — the hall-of-mirrors effect — is developing but not fully activated.

The hall-of-mirrors effect depends on table width. As light enters the table and bounces between the step facets, each reflection needs enough physical distance to build the corridor of parallel light bands that makes the shape so distinctive.

At 1ct and 6.5mm, those corridors are short. The effect is visible and real, but it intensifies significantly as the stone grows.

