      <td>1.33</td>
      <td>Prominent, visible at arm's length</td>
      <td>~37% of avg. finger</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>2.00ct</td>
      <td>9.0mm</td>
      <td>7.0mm</td>
      <td>1.29</td>
      <td>Fully developed, strong on-hand presence</td>
      <td>~43% of avg. finger</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>2.50ct</td>
      <td>9.8mm</td>
      <td>7.6mm</td>
      <td>1.29</td>
      <td>Statement size, maximum effect</td>
      <td>~47% of avg. finger</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

The jump from 1ct (6.5mm) to 1.5ct (8.0mm) adds 1.5mm of length and 1.0mm of width. In an emerald cut, that's a visible jump — you'd see it easily from arm's length. From 1ct to 2ct (9.0mm), the table expands by 2.5mm in length, which is a dramatic change in both optical presence and on-hand size.

This size progression matters when evaluating the lab step-up. A 1ct emerald cut at 6.5mm has real presence on the hand, but the same budget in lab buys a stone that's nearly 9mm long. That's not a subtle difference.

The length-to-width ratio matters too. At 1.28–1.35, the emerald cut reads as a classic rectangular step-cut. Below 1.25, it approaches a square.

Above 1.40, it looks elongated. All five natural 1ct stones in the table above fall in the 1.28–1.35 range — confirm exact L/W ratio before purchase.

