## 1.5ct Comparison: Natural vs Natural and Lab vs Lab

[![Emerald cut diamond ring showing 1.5ct scale comparison](https://ion.bluenile.com/sets/Jewelry/Photoshoot/Bluenile/BrioPackshotBox/Rings/501150/501150_M1_EMR_DIM_wht_0100CT_Y_Box5_003_1600X1600.jpg)](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings?MetalType=all&Diamonds=Dia&ShapeID=Emerald&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)

If the 1ct emerald cut feels borderline in size, the 1.5ct natural is the next step. The jump from 6.5mm to 8.0mm in length is significant — you'd see it easily. But the 1.5ct natural price changes the budget picture entirely.

The cheapest GIA-certified 1.5ct natural emerald cut in current certified market data is [$10,409](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29298663?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) for the stone alone — a [GIA 1.50ct E-VS1](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29298663?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). Add a [$690 solitaire](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/rings/petite-emerald-cut-solitaire-diamond-ring-in-14k-yellow-gold-by-james-allen-item-311196?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) and the ring starts at $11,099. That's nearly three times the natural 1ct ring budget.

