## Expert Summary

The 1ct natural emerald cut diamond ring starts at [$3,830](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29333987?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) complete with the cheapest solitaire setting. The stone at 6.5mm × 5mm shows the step-cut's hall-of-mirrors effect in developing form. It reads as a clean, elegant ring.

The lab alternative at this price point is extraordinary by comparison. A lab 1.94ct F-VVS1 emerald cut ring costs [$2,919](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29147824?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) complete — $900 less and nearly double the stone size. The stone at 8.8mm × 6.8mm shows the fully-developed hall-of-mirrors effect that the natural 1ct is approaching.

For natural buyers: buy the [D-VS1 at $3,140](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29333987?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) rather than the IF options. The IF clarity grade is invisible at 1ct — VS1 is the correct ceiling. Put the savings toward the setting.

For lab buyers: the [1.94ct F-VVS1 at $2,229](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29147824?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the entry point. The [1.90ct D-FL at $3,862](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29396015?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the step up — the price of a natural 1ct stone buys a D-FL 1.9ct lab stone that measures 8.6mm × 6.7mm.

For setting guidance on both natural and lab emerald cuts at any size, see [emerald cut diamond ring settings](/emerald-cut-diamond-ring-settings).

